The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Saturday, December 20, 2003  Nation at a Glance				 																CAT scam kingpin in CBI custody				 																																																	Patna (PTI): Ranjit Singh, the alleged kingpin of the CAT question paper leak scandal, and three of his accomplices were on Friday remanded in CBI custody for 10 days by a special court in connection with the leak of CBSE medical and dental question papers in 2003.				 																																																										The four, including Arun Kumar Sinha, Manoj Kumar and Harishanker Chaudhary, were produced before special judge B.. Sahay who remanded them in CBI custody for interrogation on a plea by special public prosecutor (CBI) L.R. Ansari.				 																																																										The special public prosecutor had urged for the accused to be sentenced to CBI custody for 15 days, but the court permitted only 10 days.				 																																																										Ansari said the gang was involved in the leak of CBSE medical and dental test papers which were sold for Rs 8-10 lakh per examinee. He said the CBI remand of the accused was also necessary as they were involved in leak of test papers of many other entrance examinations.				 																																																										Appearing for the four accused, Rajeev Ranjan Dwivedi and Harishanker Chakradhari contended that their clients were falsely implicated in the case. What is the justification of filing an FIR (in the CBSE medical/dental test case) eight months after the alleged leak of the papers? Chakradhari asked, saying the entire exercise seemed motivated.				 																																																										The defence lawyers said they apprehended that the CBI sleuths would torture their clients during interrogation and urged the court for direction to the bureau to allow at least one of the defence counsels to be present during interrogation. The court granted the plea.				 																Net quizzing for Calcutta medics  New Delhi: The National Consumer Disputes  Redressal Commission has in a first of its kind order directed  the cross-examination of five Calcutta physicians through  Internet/video conferencing in a medical negligence case,  reports our legal correspondent.				 																																																										Commission chairman Justice M.B. Shah said on Friday that the cross-examination of Sukumar Mukherjee, Baidyanath Halder, Abani Roychowdhury, Balaram Prasad and Kausik Nandy should be conducted within a month.				 																																																										The conferencing will be held between Calcutta and the US, from where complainant Kunal Saha, an AIDS specialist, will assist his counsel in questioning the accused. The commission also appointed Justice (retd) Lokeswar Prasad to cross-examine the five in Calcutta.				 																																																										Representatives of the citys AMRI-Apollo Hospital will also be cross-examined in the Rs 77.7-crore compensation case Saha filed for the wrongful death of his wife Anuradha Saha, a US-based doctor, five years ago.				 																Unknown hand in train mishap				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): Railway minister Nitish Kumar on Friday said the commissioner of railway safety has fixed primary responsibility for the fire in Golden Temple Mail (earlier known as Frontier Mail), which caused the death of 36 people, on an unidentified person.				 																																																										Replying to supplementaries during question hour in Rajya Sabha, Kumar said the unidentified person either carried or left a bag containing explosive material in a coach of the 2903 Up mail on Ludhiana-Amritsar section on May 15, 2003.				 																Namdev plea				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court on Friday rejected Namdevs plea for exemption from surrender. Another petition by the CISF constable, who has been charged with killing a senior, challenging a Bombay High Court order that denied him bail was posted for hearing on January 12.				 																Graft workshop				 																																																	Coimbatore (PTI): A one-day workshop to create awareness against rampant corruption will be held here on Sunday. Former central vigilance commissioner . Vittal and former CBI director D.R. Karthikeyan will address over 500 participants.				 																Trishul test-fired				 																																																	Balasore (PTI): Trishul, a short-range surface-to-air missile, was test-fired from the Integrated Test Range at Chandipur near here on Friday for the second time in as many days. The missile has been indigenously developed by the Defence Research and Development Organisation.				 																Life sentence				 																																																	Sonepat (PTI): Six persons have been sentenced to life imprisonment by a local court that also slapped a fine of Rs 2,000 on each in a murder case. Additional sessions judge J.S. Jangr passed the order on Thursday. A case was registered against the six on November 29, 2001, after one person complained that they had murdered his brother.				 																Lovers suicide				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): A teenage couple allegedly committed suicide early on Friday by jumping in front of a train in Kathua district reportedly because their families were against their relationship. 																		Kerala, Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh craftsmen will showcase their products in a 10-day rural technology fair beginning on Monday in Kochi. The Council for Advancement of Peoples Action and Rural Technology is organising the exhibition.
